  Total H=25 at n=6: 1440

=== Does (1+2x)² packing exist? ===
Need: 4 three-cycles forming 2 disjoint overlapping pairs
i.e., Ω restricted to 3-cycles = K_2 ⊔ K_2, with no 5-cycles
This requires:
  Pair 1: 2 overlapping 3-cycles on vertices A (|A|=4 or 5)
  Pair 2: 2 overlapping 3-cycles on vertices B, disjoint from A
  n ≥ |A| + |B| ≥ 8 (if |A|=|B|=4)
BUT n=6 only has 6 vertices! So we need |A|+|B| ≤ 6.
Min is |A|=4, |B|=4 → needs 8. IMPOSSIBLE at n=6!

Wait — overlapping means sharing vertices. Two 3-cycles sharing 2 vertices
use 4 distinct vertices. So pair 1 uses 4, pair 2 uses 4, total ≥ 8.
If pairs share vertices with each other, they're NOT disjoint → not K_2 ⊔ K_2.

UNLESS the pairs overlap by sharing 1 vertex:
  Two 3-cycles sharing 1 vertex use 5 vertices.
  Two such pairs sharing vertices between pairs → not K_2 ⊔ K_2.

CONCLUSION: (1+2x)² packing needs n ≥ 8 (two disjoint cuboid bricks)
  Each brick = 2 overlapping 3-cycles on 4 vertices (sharing edge)
  Two bricks vertex-disjoint → 8 vertices minimum

So H=25 at n=6 does NOT come from cuboid packing.
Instead it comes from a SINGLE clique of cycles.
